  "text": "## Stack Protection Mechanisms in LLVM Project\n\nThe LLVM/Clang project implements comprehensive stack protection mechanisms against buffer overflow attacks across multiple layers:\n\n### 1. StackProtector Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp)\nThis is the primary LLVM pass responsible for inserting stack protector checks. The pass implements the classic stack canary defense mechanism:\n- **StackProtector class**: A FunctionPass (legacy interface) that inserts stack protectors into functions needing protection\n- **StackProtectorPass class**: The new pass manager interface for the same functionality\n- **SSPLayoutAnalysis class**: Analyzes which allocations require stack protection and determines the layout\n- **InsertStackProtectors()**: Core function that inserts prologue code to load the stack guard value and epilogue code to check it, calling __stack_chk_fail if the guard is corrupted\n- **CreateFailBB()**: Creates the failure basic block that calls __stack_chk_fail when a stack overflow is detected\n\nThe pass loads a random guard value, stores it on the stack before local variables, and checks it upon function exit. If modified, it calls the runtime failure handler.\n\n### 2. StackProtector Header (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h)\nDeclares the pass interface with:\n- **SSPLayoutInfo struct**: Contains SSP layout mapping and configuration\n- **StackProtector class**: Legacy pass interface\n- **StackProtectorPass class**: New pass manager interface\n- Methods to determine which functions require stack protection based on language level settings\n\n### 3. SafeStack Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp)\nImplements a more sophisticated stack protection mechanism that separates safe and unsafe stack allocations:\n- **SafeStack class**: Implements the core transformation that splits stack into safe (kept in normal stack) and unsafe (explicitly allocated/managed through runtime) regions\n- **SafeStackPass class**: New pass manager interface\n- **SafeStackLegacyPass class**: Legacy interface\n- **checkStackGuard()**: Verifies the stack guard at function return points by comparing stored value against current guard\n- The pass identifies unsafe allocations (large buffers, variable-sized arrays, objects whose address is taken) and moves them to a separate unsafe stack managed by the safestack runtime library\n\n### 4. SafeStack Headers and Layout (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/SafeStack.h, llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.h)\n- **SafeStackPass**: Declares the pass interface with TargetMachine parameter\n- **StackLayout class**: Computes memory layout for unsafe stack frames, computing offsets and alignments for stack objects with coloring optimization\n- Uses **SafeStackLayout.cpp** for layout computation with proper alignment and lifetime analysis\n\n### 5. Stack Check Failure Runtime (libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp)\nProvides the runtime implementation called when stack overflow is detected:\n- **__stack_chk_fail()**: Prints \"stack smashing detected\" message and calls abort() to terminate the program\n- **__stack_chk_guard**: Global variable initialized with a random value (0xa9fff01234) that serves as the canary\n- Header declaration in **libc/src/compiler/__stack_chk_fail.h** with noreturn attribute\n\n### 6. Memory Safety Instrumentation (llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/)\nAdditional memory safety instrumentation passes:\n- **AddressSanitizer.cpp**: Instruments memory accesses to detect heap/global/stack buffer overflows, use-after-free, and other memory errors\n- **HWAddressSanitizer.cpp**: Hardware-assisted address sanitizer using tagged addressing for memory error detection\n\nThese sanitizers complement stack protectors by detecting various memory safety violations dynamically at runtime.\n\n### Integration\nThe StackProtector pass inserts checks in the IR (StackProtector.cpp:InsertStackProtectors), which is either handled by SelectionDAG (for some targets) or by SafeStack for more comprehensive protection. SafeStack's checkStackGuard() method provides additional runtime verification. When a violation is detected via any mechanism, __stack_chk_fail() is called to terminate the process safely.\n"
}
